observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the management:

(1) Require coordination between City Accountant and GSO towards the implementation of the perpetual inventory method in the recording of supplies and materials to ensure proper accounting and promote better control in the receipt and issuance of supplies and materials;

(2) Determine causes of non-recording of drugs and medicines in the inventory and its related expense account;

(3) Make proper adjustments in the inventory accounts most especially if the items do no longer exist. Inventories already issued must be expensed already;

(4) Instruct the GSO and the City Accountant to maintain updated Stock Cards and SLC and regularly reconcile records to detect discrepancies and effect immediate corrections.

(5) Establish relevant inventory account cited above.

We recommended that the LCE to direct the City Accountant and City Treasurer:

a. Not to grant cash advances to accountable officers who are not yet bonded;

b. Require its accountable officers to apply for bonds;

c. Not to allow reimbursements of representation expenses, like payment of meals and snacks, to Officers who are already granted RATA.

We recommended that the LCE require the City Accountant to;

a. Comply with the disclosure requirements of the pertinent PPSAS provisions to have fair presentation of the account balances in the FS;

b. Faithfully observe the accounting, reporting and full disclosure requirements of DRRMF in the NFS as prescribed under Annex D of COA Circular 2012-002.

c. Provide disclosures as to the Financial Expenses of the Agency.

d. Account for the cause of the abnormal balance in inventory and thereafter, prepare adjusting entries.

We recommended that the Management, thru the Office of the Provincial Engineer (OPE) and the Bids and Awards Committee and its Technical Working Group (BAC/TWG), observe the following measures:
For the BAC/TWG and OPE to submit a written justification for each of the noted lapses/deficiencies, especially that of the recommendation to award the contract to a single bidder without proper evaluation of its technical capability to undertake multiple projects with nearly simultaneous and overlapping schedules, and which effectively caused delays in the implementation of seven (7) out of the 20 projects;
For the OPE to properly monitor and supervise projects, especially those that are on-going and yet to be started projects, to ensure smooth implementation, timely completion, and immediate use thereof for the intended purposes by the target beneficiaries;
For the BAC/TWG to properly evaluate the capacities/capabilities of the commitments of bidders during the procurement process, relative to the adequacy and availability of equipment and key personnel presented in the technical documents vis-à-vis project scheduling, especially for a single contractor for multiple projects with nearly simultaneous or overlapping implementation schedules, so as to preclude delay in the completion of projects;
For the BAC/TWG to disqualify bidders whose capacities/capabilities in terms of key personnel and equipment may not meet the practical requirements of multiple projects and instead undertake to rebid and/or award other projects, especially those that are beyond a single bidder’s capability to undertake, to other interested eligible bidders to ensure that simultaneous implementation may proceed as efficiently and effectively as planned;
For the BAC/TWG to ensure that proper instructions are given to the bidders so that the Equipment Utilization Schedule will present the specific equipment unit’s availability on the exact dates that these are projected to be utilized; and
For the OPE to submit to this Office authenticated copies of the documents that may justify the delays in the implementation of the projects, i. e., to support any revisions to the work schedules such as revised PERT/CPM, contract time extensions, work suspensions and work resumption issued to the contractor, including a status report showing the percentages of slippage incurred as to date, for our evaluation/review.

We recommended that Management direct the submission, thru the Offices of the Provincial Accountant, Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) Chairperson, and BAC Secretariat, of an original or certified true copy of the following documents:
Annual Procurement Plan (APP) or Supplemental APP, which incorporates the AZD1222 vaccine, duly approved by the Provincial Governor or his authorized representative;
Proof of posting of the approved APP (or Supplemental APP) on the Procuring Entity’s (PE) website or at any conspicuous place reserved for this purpose on the premises of the PE;
Proof of posting of the required documents and information specified in Section 6, RA 11525 including the posting of advance payment as prescribed under Item 7, GPPB Circular 02-2021;
Copy of Certificate of Product Registration (CPR) or, if unavailable, Emergency Use Authorization (EUA) from Food and Drug Administration (FDA);
Certificate of Availability of Funds issued by the Provincial Accountant;
Trade Invoice pertaining to the sixth partial payment of Covid-19 Vaccine covered under JEV No. 101-2021-08-14841 dated 8/30/2021 in the amount of P7,197,352.25; and
Acknowledgement Receipt pertaining to the second, fourth, fifth and sixth partial payments of Covid-19 Vaccine covered under JEV Nos. 101-2021-08-14841, 101-21-10-18963, 101-21-11-21066 and 101-21-12-26422 dated 8/30/2021, 10/4/2021, 11/30/2021 and 12/31/2021 in the amounts of P564,299.25, P1,676,651.00, P2,472,345.00 and P8,892,811.25, respectively.

To effectively address the noted deficiencies, we recommended the following measures, partly including reiterations of the preceding year’s audit recommendations, that Management, thru the Provincial Treasurer and the Provincial Accountant, shall:
reconcile the Cashier-Designate’s book balance with the accounting records at least once in every quarter in accordance with accounting and auditing regulations; to serve as an effective control measure to avoid errors in the reporting and recording of collections and deposits;
require the Liquidating Officer (LO), before preparing his Report of Collection and Deposit (RCD), to conduct a thorough verification of the RCDs of the Cashier-Designate to ascertain the accuracy of the remitted/deposited collections vis-à-vis the amounts indicated in the Official Receipts;
ascertain the accuracy of the RCDs of all AOs/LOs before preparing the RCD of the Provincial Treasurer;
require the Provincial Treasurer/Cashier or any authorized employee under her office other than the cashier-designate or all other field office AOs/LOs, to sign the deposit slips and actually make the deposits in accordance with Sections 32 and 35 of the MNGAS-LGUs;
require the Cashier-Designate to:
reconcile on a daily frequency the cashbook balance with that of the cash on hand to avoid the recurrence of errors;
exercise the utmost care in the recording of transactions in the cashbook, as basis for the accurate reporting of collections in the RCD; and
ensure that RCDs are prepared together with the turnover of all collections at the close of each business day;
require a written explanation from the Cashier-Designate within seventy-two (72) hours from receipt of the letter requiring the same for:
the various errors in recording and reporting collections and deposits during the period under cash examination;
the deviation from the prescribed requirement of RCD preparation at the close of each business day; and
the departure from the prescribed turnover of collections at the close of each business day resulting to lengthy delays in the remittance of collections and maintaining huge accumulated daily balances of the collections after each remittance/deposit while making partial deposits instead of depositing the full amount of collections on hand at the end of each business day.

We recommended that Management, thru the Office of the Provincial Accountant:
shall enforce the liquidation of cash advances of Accountable Officers (AO)/officials/employees/ who are still active and connected with the agency;
strictly comply with the limit of cash advance to be granted to a regular/special disbursing officer taking into account the requirements of the agency for two (2) months and refrain from granting additional cash advances unless the liquidation of previous cash advance is submitted;
issue demand letters thru post mail to the last known address of former AO/officials/employees who can no longer be traced, or request Certification of no residence in the barangay of the municipality/city of last known address; and
update the subsidiary ledgers (SL) containing the details required in Volume II, Section 10 of the Manual on the New Government Accounting System (MNGAS) to facilitate the preparation and issuance of demand letters.

We recommended that Management direct the submission, thru the Offices of the Provincial Accountant, Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) Chairperson, and BAC Secretariat, of original or certified true copy of the following documents:
Proof/s of posting of the Notices of Award (NOA) in the PhilGEPs, the website of the procuring entity, and at any conspicuous place reserved for this purpose in the premises of the procuring entity;
Copy/ies of the Annual Procurement Plan (APP) or pertinent portion thereof pertaining to each procurement transaction;
BAC Resolution recommending award of contract to the Lowest Calculated Responsive Bid (LCRB) for each procurement transaction;
Price quotation/bids/final offers from at least three invited suppliers and the corresponding Abstract of submitted Price Quotation in the purchase of medicines as per JEV No. 101-21-06-10503 dated June 29, 2021; and
Copy of the supplier’s Mayor’s/Business Permit, Income/Business Tax Return (for ABCs above P500K) and Omnibus Sworn Statement for each procurement transaction with the exception of JEV Nos. 101-21-06-10047, 101-21-06-10048, 101-21-06-10503, and 101-21-08-14187.

